                         versus hν). SnO2 and Spiro-OMeTAD energy level positions are determined using the reference [37]. These band edge positions and Fermi energies of the IE and control perovskite films are depicted in Fig. 4b, c and d. A comparison with the control film shows that the Fermi energy level of the IE film shifts upward by 0.15 eV, while the conduction band (E

                           c
                        ) shifts upward by only 0.03 eV. Based on the earlier report, the coordination of CDs with perovskite reduced I− vacancies defects density, which reduced the n-type doping effect [38]. As for PE perovskite film, the position of the valence band shifted from –5.38 eV to –5.15 eV, indicating that it displays more n-type properties which may inhibit hole extraction. The shifted band energy may be due to electron transfer between carbon dots and perovskites. CDs contain an amine group which is an electron donor, so it increases the electron concentration within perovskites and thus up-shifts the maximum energy of the valence band [39].

As mentioned that interface engineering facilitates electron extraction at ETL interface. In order to further understand the process of electron extraction in the IE device, it is necessary to directly characterize the property of the buried interface. Kelvin probe force microscopy (KPFM) was used to compare IE film buried interface potentials with control films. It could be seen in Fig. S3 in Supporting Information that the buried interface in IE film exhibits a higher surface potential than that in the control film, which facilitates electron extraction. Combined with the enhanced PL intensity, the improved Vbi ensures efficient charge collection, leading to higher current density (J

                           sc

                        ). These above results suggest that IE achieves defect passivation without hammering carrier extraction, which could explain the performance enhancement.
